  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence across borders\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n3. Standardization of Legal Frameworks\n- Establishing common definitions of money laundering\n- Creating consistent regulatory approaches\n- Developing uniform reporting and disclosure requirements\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Countries adopting international standards into domestic legislation\n- Implementing Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Establishing suspicious transaction reporting systems\n\n5. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Cross-border investigations\n- Coordinated law enforcement efforts\n- Shared financial intelligence units\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International sanctions for non-compliance\n- Pressure to meet global anti-money laundering standards\n- Potential economic consequences for inadequate legal frameworks\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
